SUMMARY: Chapter 13, in Renfrew & Bahn's textbook (Archaeology: Theories, Methods, and Practice), provides five case studies to aid student comprehension of the preceding 12 chapters and approaches to understanding and interpreting past societies.
(a). Oaxaca Projects (Central America);
(b). The Calusa of Florida (Southeast U.S.);
(c). Australia hunter-gatherers;
(d). Khok Phanom Di (Southeast Asia);
(e). York/Jorvik Viking settlement (U.K.).

In my view, this is one of the best college textbooks available, and is invaluable for students, archaeologists, and the public in general, to obtain a top notch overview of approaching and interpreting the archaeological record. UPDATED April 2021.

Archaeologically, District Loralai is one of the most important regions of north-eastern Balochistan Province of Pakistan. It is centrally located between South Asia, Iranian Plateau and Central Asia. The region has not been fully explored by archaeologists and historians as yet and the history of the region does not go beyond 14th century CE.  Researches by archaeologists in the last one century have led to the documentation of twenty-five archaeological sites in Loralai District.
Previous archaeological surveys in the Loralai District and Balochistan Province were based upon village-to-village methodologies. The present survey was carried in Tehsil Bori of District Loralai. Through the survey of ten transects, a total of twenty-six archaeological sites were discovered.  These archaeological sites were classified into 8 single-period and 13 multi-period sites, which included 6 Kot Dijian and 5 Harappan/Indus Civilization sites. Previous research suggested the presence of 10 Kot Dijian sites, including Dabar Kot, in District Loralai. The Discovery of large number of Kot Dijian and Harappan sites in a limited survey region suggests that District Loralai was not marginal when Kot Dijians and/or Pre-Harappans were laying the foundations of the Indus Civilization.  

Key words: Tehsil Bori; Loralai District; Balochistan; Transect Survey; Systematic Survey; Settlement History; Landscape Choices; Kot Dijian culture; Harappans; Indus Civilization;
